Description: CVE-2026-58471 - Fix buffer overflow in filename conversion
 GNU Wget <=1.25.0 has a heap-based buffer overflow in convert_fname()
 in src/url.c (CWE-122). When the iconv output buffer is too small the
 E2BIG reallocation branch miscalculated the remaining space by mixing
 done/len/outlen, causing subsequent iconv writes to overflow the heap
 buffer. A malicious server response containing a filename that
 requires character-set conversion (via Content-Disposition or the
 URL) can trigger the overflow.
 .
 This patch backports the upstream fix by tracking the actually used
 bytes (s - converted_fname) when reallocating, ensuring the buffer
 always grows, and recomputing outlen from the new length and used
 offset. It also replaces the fragile "len - outlen - done" null
 terminator computation with a direct write through the current write
 pointer s.
Origin: upstream, commit:c2640fe5171c59f87c58dc9fcb195b2d18b010ee
 https://gitlab.com/gnuwget/wget/-/commit/c2640fe5171c59f87c58dc9fcb195b2d18b010ee
Author: Arkadi Vainbrand <arkadva8@gmail.com>
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1141689
Last-Update: 2026-07-12

--- a/src/url.c
+++ b/src/url.c
@@ -1599,7 +1599,7 @@ convert_fname (char *fname)
   const char *from_encoding = opt.encoding_remote;
   const char *to_encoding = opt.locale;
   iconv_t cd;
-  size_t len, done, inlen, outlen;
+  size_t len, inlen, outlen;
   char *s;
   const char *orig_fname;
 
@@ -1621,7 +1621,6 @@ convert_fname (char *fname)
   inlen = strlen (fname);
   len = outlen = inlen * 2;
   converted_fname = s = xmalloc (outlen + 1);
-  done = 0;
 
   for (;;)
     {
@@ -1629,7 +1628,7 @@ convert_fname (char *fname)
       if (iconv (cd, (ICONV_CONST char **) &fname, &inlen, &s, &outlen) == 0
           && iconv (cd, NULL, NULL, &s, &outlen) == 0)
         {
-          *(converted_fname + len - outlen - done) = '\0';
+          *s = '\0';
           iconv_close (cd);
           DEBUGP (("Converted file name '%s' (%s) -> '%s' (%s)\n",
                    orig_fname, from_encoding, converted_fname, to_encoding));
@@ -1652,10 +1651,17 @@ convert_fname (char *fname)
         }
       else if (errno == E2BIG) /* Output buffer full */
         {
-          done = len;
-          len = outlen = done + inlen * 2;
-          converted_fname = xrealloc (converted_fname, outlen + 1);
-          s = converted_fname + done;
+          size_t used = s - converted_fname;
+          size_t newlen = used + inlen * 2 + 1;
+
+          /* Ensure we actually grow the buffer */
+          if (newlen <= len)
+            newlen = len * 2;
+
+          converted_fname = xrealloc (converted_fname, newlen + 1);
+          len = newlen;
+          s = converted_fname + used;
+          outlen = len - used;
         }
       else /* Weird, we got an unspecified error */
         {
Description: Fix CVE-2026-58472 integer + heap buffer overflow in html_quote_string
 GNU Wget's html_quote_string() in src/convert.c uses a signed int counter
 to accumulate the required output buffer size while walking the input
 string. A remote attacker able to have wget parse an HTML attribute
 containing a large number of characters requiring entity encoding
 (e.g. many '&', '<', '>', '"', or ' ') can cause the counter to
 overflow, resulting in an undersized xmalloc() allocation followed by
 a heap buffer overflow when the encoded string is written into the
 buffer.
 .
 This patch changes the counter to size_t and uses gnulib's
 INT_ADD_OK() macro (from <intprops.h>) to detect any overflow while
 computing the required size. On overflow the function logs a debug
 message and aborts, preventing memory corruption. intprops.h is
 provided by the pre-bootstrapped gnulib sources shipped in the Debian
 orig tarball (lib/intprops.h), so no additional bootstrap step is
 required for the Debian build.
Origin: upstream, commit:dd692d9cea5335b181d877ae917fe6e75587a812
Bug: https://gitlab.com/gnuwget/wget/-/commit/dd692d9cea5335b181d877ae917fe6e75587a812
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1141689
Author: Tim Ruehsen <tim.ruehsen@gmx.de>
Last-Update: 2026-06-29

